article(class="intStuff shop")  
	h2(class="title") Once you know what you're looking for, it's time to plan your trip to the grocery store or a local farmers' market. 
	h1(class="titleSmall") TIPS FOR MAKING <span class="purple">YOUR SHOPPING LIST</span>
	section(class="row steps")
		div(class="col-lg-6 col-md-6")
			div(class="listContent")
				header
					h2 Start with what you have 
				article Check your fridge, freezer, and cabinets. Plan meals that use what you already have in the house.
		
			div(class="listContent")
				header
					h2 Think about the fruits and veggies first  
				article Meals based around fruits and veggies are cheaper&mdash;and better for you&mdash;than meat. <a href=" http://www.sustainabletable.org/seasonalfoodguide/" target="_blank">Look at what's in season</a>, what looks good, and what is on sale&mdash;and think of how you can base meals around these fruits and veggies.

			div(class="listContent")
				header
					h2 Look up budget-friendly recipes
				article There are lots of sites with healthy, low-cost recipes. Try <a href="https://www.foodhero.org/recipes/healthy-recipes" target="_blank">Food Hero</a> or <a href="http://www.extension.iastate.edu/foodsavings/recipes/all" target="_blank">Spend Smart Eat Smart</a> for ideas. Get your family in on the fun by asking them to rate new meals on a scale of 1 to 5. When you find a recipe that your family rates a 3 or above, keep it on hand for future meal planning!	
		

		div(class="col-lg-6 col-md-6") 
			div(class="listContent") 
				header
					h2 Plan for 5-6 meals with extra for leftovers
				article Cooking larger batches helps you save money by buying ingredients in larger quantities&mdash;and using the leftovers for lunch.

			div(class="listContent")
				header
					h2 KEEP CHEAP AND EASY-TO-COOK STAPLE FOODS TO MAKE MEALTIME SIMPLE 
				article Buy extras of foods that you can use regularly and that keep on the shelf (called staple foods) when they're on sale, like rice, dry beans, peanut butter, canned soup, and canned or frozen vegetables. Having staples of cheap and easy-to-cook foods can make mealtime simple.

